                <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#d57a66] mb-2">Week 1: Pronunciation Focus - Mastering Initial Sounds</h1>\
                <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-6">Getting the basic sounds right is crucial for clear communication. This section highlights common pronunciation challenges for Week 1's vocabulary and provides tips.</p>\
                <div class="grid grid-cols-1 gap-6">\
                    <div class="card p-6">\
                        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Focus Sounds for Week 1</h2>\
                        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 text-gray-700">\
                            <li><strong>\'cb (Schwa):</strong> This is perhaps the most unique Albanian vowel. It's often unstressed, like the 'a' in 'about'. At the end of words (e.g., 'buk\'eb'), it can be almost silent. Practice saying words like 'buk\'eb' (bread) and 'k\'ebng\'eb' (song), trying to barely pronounce the final '\'eb'.</li>\
                            <li><strong>R vs Rr:</strong> Albanian has two 'R' sounds. The single 'R' is a soft, tapped 'r' (like in Spanish 'pero'). The 'Rr' is a strong, rolled 'r' (like in Spanish 'perro' or Scottish 'r'). Practice 'rrug\'eb' (road - with Rr) vs. just a tap.</li>\
                            <li><strong>J:</strong> Pronounced like the 'y' in 'yes' or 'yogurt'. (e.g., 'jam' - I am, 'je' - you are).</li>\
                            <li><strong>K:</strong> Often very crisp and slightly aspirated, similar to English but sometimes more emphatic.</li>\
                            <li><strong>Th:</strong> Like the 'th' in 'think' (unvoiced). (e.g., 'thjesht\'eb' - simple).</li>\
                            <li><strong>Dh:</strong> Like the 'th' in 'this' (voiced). (e.g., 'dhurat\'eb' - gift).</li>\
                        </ul>\
\
                        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 mt-6">Tips for Clear Pronunciation</h2>\
                        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700">\
                            <li><strong>Listen Actively:</strong> Pay close attention to native speakers, especially for the '\'eb' and the two 'r' sounds. Online dictionaries with audio are invaluable.</li>\
                            <li><strong>Slow Down:</strong> Don't rush your pronunciation, especially when starting. Articulate each sound clearly.</li>\
                            <li><strong>Mimic:</strong> Try to mimic the intonation and rhythm of Albanian speakers, not just individual sounds.</li>\
                            <li><strong>Practice Minimal Pairs:</strong> Find words that differ only by one sound you're struggling with (e.g., 'rrug\'eb' vs. a word with 'R') to train your ear and mouth.</li>\
                        </ul>\
                    </div>\
                </div>\
            </div>\
