                <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#d57a66] mb-2">Week 2: Theory Deep Dive - Nouns & Descriptions</h1>\
                <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-6">Delve deeper into the rules governing Albanian nouns, including gender, articles, and pluralization. These are crucial for building complex sentences.</p>\
                <div class="grid grid-cols-1 gap-6">\
                    <div class="card p-6">\
                        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Core Grammar Concepts</h2>\
                        <div class="accordion accordion-nested">\
                            <h4 class="accordion-header font-medium cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center p-3 rounded-t-lg border-b"><span>Nouns & Gender</span> <span>&#9662;</span></h4>\
                            <div class="accordion-content p-3 rounded-b-lg">\
                                <p>All Albanian nouns are either <strong>Masculine (Mashkullor)</strong> or <strong>Feminine (Fem\'ebror)</strong>. This inherent gender affects the definite articles, indefinite articles, and adjectives that accompany the noun.</p>\
                                <p class="mt-2 font-bold">General Rules for Gender (with exceptions):</p>\
                                <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-sm mt-2">\
                                    <li><strong>Masculine Nouns:</strong> Often end in a consonant (e.g., 'lib\'ebr' - book, 'mal' - mountain, 'qytet' - city) or sometimes in '-\'eb' (e.g., 'djal\'eb' - boy).</li>\
                                    <li><strong>Feminine Nouns:</strong> Often end in a vowel, most commonly '-a', '-e', or '-i' (e.g., 'sht\'ebpi' - house, 'tavolin\'eb' - table, 'vajz\'eb' - girl).</li>\
                                </ul>\
                                <p class="mt-2">It's best to learn the gender of a noun along with the noun itself.</p>\
                            </div>\
                        </div>\
                        <div class="accordion accordion-nested mt-2">\
                            <h4 class="accordion-header font-medium cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center p-3 rounded-t-lg border-b"><span>Definite and Indefinite Articles</span> <span>&#9662;</span></h4>\
                            <div class="accordion-content p-3 rounded-b-lg">\
                                <p>Unlike English, where 'the' is a separate word, in Albanian, the definite article is a suffix attached directly to the noun. The indefinite article 'a/an' is a separate word.</p>\
                                <p class="mt-2 font-bold">Indefinite Article (a/an):</p>\
                                <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-sm mt-2">\
                                    <li>Use <strong>'nj\'eb'</strong> before the noun, regardless of gender.</li>\
                                    <li>Examples: <em>nj\'eb lib\'ebr</em> (a book), <em>nj\'eb sht\'ebpi</em> (a house), <em>nj\'eb telefon</em> (a phone).</li>\
                                </ul>\
                                <p class="mt-4 font-bold">Definite Article (the):</p>\
                                <p class="mt-2">The suffix depends on the noun's gender and its ending:</p>\
                                <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-sm mt-2">\
                                    <li><strong>Masculine Nouns:</strong>\
                                        <ul>\
                                            <li>Ending in consonant: usually <strong>'-i'</strong> (e.g., lib\'ebr -> libri, mal -> mali)</li>\
                                            <li>Ending in 'k', 'g', 'h': usually <strong>'-u'</strong> (e.g., park -> parku, shteg -> shtegu)</li>\
                                            <li>Ending in '-\'eb': often <strong>'-u'</strong> (e.g., djal\'eb -> djali)</li>\
                                        </ul>\
                                    </li>\
                                    <li><strong>Feminine Nouns:</strong>\
                                        <ul>\
                                            <li>Ending in '-\'eb': usually <strong>'-a'</strong> (e.g., sht\'ebpi -> sht\'ebpia, buk\'eb -> buka)</li>\
                                            <li>Ending in other vowels: usually <strong>'-a'</strong> (e.g., tavolin\'eb -> tavolina)</li>\
                                        </ul>\
                                    </li>\
                                </ul>\
                                <p class="mt-2">This is a simplified overview, as there are exceptions and more complex rules, but these are the most common patterns for a beginner.</p>\
                            </div>\
                        </div>\
                         <div class="accordion accordion-nested mt-2">\
                            <h4 class="accordion-header font-medium cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center p-3 rounded-t-lg border-b"><span>Plural Forms of Nouns</span> <span>&#9662;</span></h4>\
                            <div class="accordion-content p-3 rounded-b-lg">\
                                <p>Forming plurals in Albanian can be complex, with various rules depending on gender and ending. Here are some common patterns for indefinite plurals:</p>\
                                <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-sm mt-2">\
                                    <li><strong>Masculine Nouns:</strong>\
                                        <ul>\
                                            <li>Many add <strong>'-a'</strong> (e.g., lib\'ebr -> libra - books, mal -> male - mountains)</li>\
                                            <li>Some add <strong>'-inj'</strong> (e.g., qytet -> qytetinj - cities)</li>\
                                        </ul>\
                                    </li>\
                                    <li><strong>Feminine Nouns:</strong>\
                                        <ul>\
                                            <li>Many change '-\'eb' to <strong>'-a'</strong> (e.g., sht\'ebpi -> sht\'ebpia - houses, got\'eb -> gota - glasses)</li>\
                                            <li>Some take <strong>'-ra'</strong> (e.g., dor\'eb -> dora - hands)</li>\
                                        </ul>\
                                    </li>\
                                </ul>\
                                <p class="mt-2">Definite plurals add another suffix on top of the indefinite plural form (e.g., libra -> librat - the books, sht\'ebpia -> sht\'ebpit\'eb - the houses). Focus on recognizing the patterns and building your vocabulary with both singular and plural forms.</p>\
                            </div>\
                        </div>\
                    </div>\
                </div>\
            </div>\
