                <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#d57a66] mb-2">Week 2: Pronunciation Focus - Noun Endings</h1>\
                <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-6">Mastering the subtle pronunciation of noun endings, especially for definite and plural forms, is key for clarity. This section provides tips.</p>\
                <div class="grid grid-cols-1 gap-6">\
                    <div class="card p-6">\
                        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Focus Sounds for Week 2</h2>\
                        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 text-gray-700">\
                            <li><strong>-i (Masculine Definite):</strong> The 'i' at the end of masculine definite nouns is typically pronounced clearly, like the 'ee' in 'see'. (e.g., 'libri' - the book).</li>\
                            <li><strong>-u (Masculine Definite):</strong> The 'u' in words like 'parku' (the park) is a pure 'oo' sound, as in 'moon'.</li>\
                            <li><strong>-a (Feminine Definite):</strong> The 'a' at the end of feminine definite nouns is a clear 'ah' sound, as in 'father'. (e.g., 'sht\'ebpia' - the house).</li>\
                            <li><strong>Plural Endings:</strong> Pay attention to the subtle differences in plural endings.\
                                <ul>\
                                    <li>Masculine '-a' (e.g., 'libra'): The 'a' is again a clear 'ah' sound.</li>\
                                    <li>Feminine '-t\'eb' (e.g., 'sht\'ebpit\'eb'): The '\'eb' here is pronounced, and the 't' is a soft dental 't'.</li>\
                                </ul>\
                            </li>\
                            <li><strong>Double Consonants (e.g., -ll):</strong> Words like 'yll' (star) have 'll' which is a "dark l" (like the 'l' in 'ball'). Ensure you differentiate this from the regular 'l' (like in 'lis' - oak), which is a "light l" (tip of tongue on upper teeth).</li>\
                        </ul>\
\
