                <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#d57a66] mb-2">Week 4: Theory Deep Dive - Present Continuous & Pronouns</h1>\
                <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-6">Understand the mechanics of describing actions in progress, including the versatile 'po' construction and the use of direct object pronouns.</p>\
                <div class="grid grid-cols-1 gap-6">\
                    <div class="card p-6">\
                        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Core Grammar Concepts</h2>\
                        <div class="accordion accordion-nested">\
                            <h4 class="accordion-header font-medium cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center p-3 rounded-t-lg border-b"><span>The "Po" Construction (Present Continuous)</span> <span>&#9662;</span></h4>\
                            <div class="accordion-content p-3 rounded-b-lg">\
                                <p>To express an action happening right now (equivalent to "am/is/are -ing" in English), Albanian uses the particle <strong>'po'</strong> placed directly before the conjugated verb in the simple present tense.</p>\
                                <p class="mt-2 font-bold">Structure: Subject + po + Verb (Present Tense Form)</p>\
                                <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-sm mt-2">\
                                    <li>Un\'eb <strong>po lexoj</strong>. (I am reading.)</li>\
                                    <li>Ti <strong>po punon</strong>. (You are working.)</li>\
                                    <li>Ai <strong>po ha</strong>. (He is eating.)</li>\
                                    <li>Na <strong>po pijm\'eb</strong> kafe. (We are drinking coffee.)</li>\
                                </ul>\
                                <p class="mt-4 font-bold">Negation with "Po" Construction:</p>\
                                <p>To negate an action happening now, 'nuk' comes before 'po'.</p>\
                                <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-sm mt-2">\
                                    <li>Un\'eb <strong>nuk po lexoj</strong>. (I am not reading.)</li>\
                                    <li>Ajo <strong>nuk po fle</strong>. (She is not sleeping.)</li>\
                                </ul>\
                            </div>\
                        </div>\
                        <div class="accordion accordion-nested mt-2">\
                            <h4 class="accordion-header font-medium cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center p-3 rounded-t-lg border-b"><span>Direct Object Pronouns</span> <span>&#9662;</span></h4>\
                            <div class="accordion-content p-3 rounded-b-lg">\
                                <p>Direct object pronouns replace nouns that receive the action of the verb. In Albanian, they typically come *before* the verb, or between 'po' and the verb in the continuous tense.</p>\
                                <p class="mt-2 font-bold">Common Direct Object Pronouns:</p>\
                                <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-sm mt-2">\
                                    <li><strong>m\'eb</strong> (me) - Ti m\'eb sheh. (You see me.) / Ti po m\'eb sheh. (You are seeing me.)</li>\
                                    <li><strong>t\'eb</strong> (you, singular informal) - Un\'eb t\'eb shoh. (I see you.) / Un\'eb po t\'eb shoh. (I am seeing you.)</li>\
                                    <li><strong>e</strong> (him/it, masculine singular; her/it, feminine singular) - E shoh librin. (I see the book - masculine). E shoh tavolin\'ebn. (I see the table - feminine).</li>\
                                    <li><strong>i</strong> (them, masculine plural) - I shoh burrat. (I see the men.)</li>\
                                    <li><strong>i</strong> (them, feminine plural) - I shoh grat\'eb. (I see the women.)</li>\
                                    <li><strong>na</strong> (us) - Ai na njeh. (He knows us.)</li>\
                                    <li><strong>ju</strong> (you, plural/formal) - Ata ju presin. (They are waiting for you.)</li>\
                                </ul>\
