                <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#d57a66] mb-2">Week 4: Pronunciation Focus - Smoothness & Connected Speech</h1>\
                <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-6">This week introduces structures that require smooth transitions and attention to connected speech, especially with the 'po' construction and pronouns.</p>\
                <div class="grid grid-cols-1 gap-6">\
                    <div class="card p-6">\
                        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Focus Sounds & Connected Speech for Week 4</h2>\
                        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 text-gray-700">\
                            <li><strong>"Po" construction:</strong> When "po" is used, it should flow smoothly into the verb. Avoid a hard pause between them. Practice: "po lexoj" (po-lek-soj), "po ha" (po-ha).</li>\
                            <li><strong>Pronoun Placement:</strong> Direct object pronouns (m\'eb, t\'eb, e, i, na, ju) are unstressed and should blend with the words around them.\
                                <ul>\
                                    <li>"po e shoh" (po-e-shoh) - "e" blends with "po" and "shoh".</li>\
                                    <li>"po m\'eb d\'ebgjon" (po-muh-duh-gjon) - "m\'eb" is a light sound.</li>\
                                </ul>\
                            </li>\
                            <li><strong>Adverbs:</strong> Pronounce adverbs clearly, ensuring the final sounds are distinct. For instance, the '\'eb' in 'shpejt\'eb' or 'ngadal\'eb' should be a soft schwa.</li>\
                            <li><strong>Verbs ending in 'j':</strong> Be mindful of the 'j' sound (like 'y' in 'yes') at the end of verb stems like 'd\'ebgjoj', 'shkruaj' when followed by different endings.</li>\
