                <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-6">Understanding the social rhythms and deep-rooted hospitality in Albanian culture can enhance your communication and interactions.</p>\
                <div class="grid grid-cols-1 gap-6">\
                    <div class="card p-6">\
                        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">The Art of Conversation</h2>\
                        <p class="text-gray-700">Albanians generally enjoy conversation and social interaction. Questions like "\'c7ka po b\'ebn?" (What are you doing?) or "Ku po shkon?" (Where are you going?) are common friendly inquiries, even if they sometimes feel direct to non-Albanians. They often serve as icebreakers and a way to show interest and connection. Be prepared for conversations to be lively and sometimes involve more than one person speaking at a time, especially among close friends.</p>\
\
                        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 mt-6">Hospitality and Offering (The "Merr!" mentality)</h2>\
                        <p class="text-gray-700">Hospitality (mikpritja) is a cornerstone of Albanian culture, rooted in the ancient code of Besa. If you are a guest, expect to be offered food and drink repeatedly. It is polite to initially refuse once or twice (e.g., "Faleminderit, jo" - Thank you, no), but then to accept. Hosts often insist with phrases like "Merr!" (Take!), "Ha!" (Eat!), or "Pi!" (Drink!). It's a way for them to show care and generosity.</p>\
\
                        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 mt-6">Public Life vs. Private Sphere</h2>\
                        <p class="text-gray-700">There's often a clear distinction between public and private life. While public spaces like cafes and promenades are vibrant and social, the home is a very private and sacred space, usually reserved for family and very close friends. Being invited into an Albanian home is a significant sign of trust and respect, indicating that you are considered part of their inner circle.</p>\
